## 📊 Supported Datasets

| Dataset | Rows | Source |
|---|---|---|
| loan_data.csv (default) | 9,578 | Kaggle |
| Credit Risk Dataset | 32,581 | [Kaggle](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/laotse/credit-risk-dataset) |
| Home Credit Default Risk | 300,000+ | [Kaggle](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/home-credit-default-risk) |
| Lending Club | 2M+ | [Kaggle](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/wordsforthewise/lending-club) |
| German Credit Risk | 1,000 | [UCI](https://archive.ics.uci.edu/dataset/144/statlog+german+credit+data) |

> ⚡ Datasets above 50,000 rows are auto-sampled for performance.

The app auto-detects the target column from: `not.fully.paid`, `default`, `loan_status`, `charged_off`

---

## 🧠 ML Concepts Used

### Logistic Regression
Uses the **Sigmoid function** to convert a linear score into a probability:

```
σ(z) = 1 / (1 + e^(-z))
where z = w₁x₁ + w₂x₂ + ... + b
```

If probability > 0.5 → predicted default

### Class Imbalance Handling
Only ~16% of borrowers default — the dataset is imbalanced. Fixed using:
```python
LogisticRegression(class_weight='balanced')
```
This penalizes misclassifying the minority class (defaulters) more heavily.

### Evaluation Metrics

| Metric | What It Measures |
|---|---|
| **Accuracy** | Overall correct predictions |
| **AUC-ROC** | Model's ability to separate classes |
| **Precision** | Of predicted defaults, how many were real |
| **Recall** | Of real defaults, how many were caught |
| **F1 Score** | Balance between precision and recall |

> Why AUC instead of just accuracy? With 84% no-default rate, always predicting "no default" gives 84% accuracy — meaningless. AUC measures true discrimination power.

---

## 📈 Visualizations Explained

| Graph | What It Shows |
|---|---|
| Class Distribution | Balance between defaulters and non-defaulters |
| ROC Curve | How well the model separates the two classes |
| Confusion Matrix | Breakdown of correct/incorrect predictions |
| Feature Importance | Which features drive default prediction most |
| Probability Distribution | Model confidence across all borrowers |
| Correlation Heatmap | How each feature relates to the default target |

---

## 🎯 Interview Q&A (Key Concepts)

**Q: Why Logistic Regression and not Linear Regression?**
> Linear Regression can predict values outside [0,1]. Sigmoid function in Logistic Regression constrains output to a valid probability.

**Q: What is class imbalance and how did you handle it?**
> Only ~16% of borrowers default. Using `class_weight='balanced'` makes the model pay more attention to the minority class.

**Q: Why AUC-ROC over accuracy?**
> Accuracy is misleading on imbalanced data. AUC-ROC measures the model's true ability to separate defaulters from non-defaulters regardless of threshold.

**Q: What does the confusion matrix tell you?**
> True Positives = caught defaulters, False Negatives = missed defaulters (most dangerous), False Positives = wrongly flagged good borrowers.

